Canadian figure skating champions

Guy Spurrier

2018-01-12

These four plots were prepared for publication with final day coverage of the 2018 Canadian figure skating championships. There were a few troubles with the data, as seen in the code notations below. The fixes arent particularly elegant, but they served their purposes.

(And yes, truth be told, this is a data-viz exercise that probably could be best solved with a table rather than a plot.)

Future learning will have to tackle more efficient solutions for dealing with:

the misrepresented accented characters (as years are added, the hard-coded fixes to names will not be work because the row positions will have changed), string replacements (see the Constance Wilson problem in the womens section and the Gold-Silver-Bronze alphabetizing problem)

The biggest problem was with the plot titles. For readability, its best to use horizontal bar charts. Previous plotting exercises showed that ggplot attaches the plot titles, subtitles and captions to the data panel of the plot, not the entire area. As plots were prepared with longer names in the y axis, the plot title and subtitle became more obviously our of whack. Attempts to use hjust inside individual parameters of theme() proved to be unsatisfying. They also became unworkable when saving the plot from default to the desired 640px width.

After creating and publishing the plots as they were, I went back to see if I could find a better solution. I finally discovered the cowplot package, which

library(RColorBrewer)

devtools::install_github("sfirke/janitor") # advanced github version with 2&3-level tabyls
## Skipping install of 'janitor' from a github remote, the SHA1 (d71ab8cc) has not changed since last install.
##   Use `force = TRUE` to force installation
fskt <- read_csv("~/Documents/R/Data files/Olympics/CdnFigureSkatingChampions.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Year = col_integer(),
##   Location = col_character(),
##   Category = col_character(),
##   Gold = col_character(),
##   Silver = col_character(),
##   Bronze = col_character()
## )
fskt$Category <- as.factor(fskt$Category)

#add 2018 medallists
fskt[186,4:6] <- c("Patrick Chan", "Keegan Messing", "Nam Nguyen")

#get counts for each colour of medal
menGold <- fskt %>% filter(Category == "Men's singles") %>% count(Gold) %>% arrange(desc(n))
menSilver <- fskt %>% filter(Category == "Men's singles") %>% count(Silver) %>% arrange(desc(n))
menBronze <- fskt %>% filter(Category == "Men's singles") %>% count(Bronze) %>% arrange(desc(n))

#fix the column names so the join below works properly
colnames(menGold) <- c("Skater", "Gold")
colnames(menSilver) <- c("Skater", "Silver")
colnames(menBronze) <- c("Skater", "Bronze")

#join the three tables is there a way to join them all at once? 
#dplyr documentation indicates you can only do two a time
menJoin <- full_join(menGold, menSilver)
## Joining, by = "Skater"
menMedals <- full_join(menJoin, menBronze)
## Joining, by = "Skater"
#remove the row that contains all the NA results (the years no competitions were held or not all medals were awarded)
menMedals <- slice(menMedals, -3)

#change all the remaining NA to 0, which is more accurate
menMedals[is.na(menMedals)] <- 0

#add medal totals for each skater
menMedals$Total <- menMedals$Gold + menMedals$Silver + menMedals$Bronze

#remove tibbles that are no longer needed
rm(menJoin, menGold, menSilver, menBronze)

subPlot <- menMedals %>% slice(1:22) #take all the men with 2+ gold medals

#gather menMedals into a plottable long tibble 
plotMen <- gather(subPlot, key = Medal, value = Count, c(Gold, Silver, Bronze))
plotMen$Total <- NULL #remove unnecessary column

#fix the names with incorrect accented characters
#plotMen[c(54,139,224),1] <- "Jayson Dnomme"
#plotMen[c(33,118,203),1] <- "Sbastian Britten"

#change the medal string for alphabetical plotting purposes
flipThese <- plotMen$Medal
flipThese <- flipThese %>% str_replace_all(pattern = "Gold", replacement = "1.Gold")
flipThese <- flipThese %>% str_replace_all(pattern = "Silver", replacement = "2.Silver")
flipThese <- flipThese %>% str_replace_all(pattern = "Bronze", replacement = "3.Bronze")
plotMen$Medal <- flipThese
plotMen$Medal <- as.factor(plotMen$Medal)

quartzFonts(ANXTC = c("Avenir Next Condensed Regular", "Avenir Next Condensed Demi Bold", "Avenir Next Condensed Italic", "Avenir Next Condensed Demi Bold Italic"))

ggplot(plotMen) +
  geom_col(aes(x = reorder(Skater, +Count), y = Count, fill = Medal)) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "ANXTC"), plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold"), plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 13, face = "plain"), axis.title.x = element_text(size = 13, face = "plain"), axis.title.y = element_text(size = 13, face = "plain"), legend.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"), legend.text = element_text(size = 12, face = "plain"), legend.direction = "horizontal", legend.position = "top", legend.justification = c(0,1), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 11, face = "plain"), axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12, face = "plain")) +
  labs(title = "Mens grand champions", subtitle = "All the men who have two more Canadian figure skating gold medals, listed with all podium finishes", x = NULL, y = "Medals", caption = "Data source: Wikipedia.com  |  Postmedia Sports") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(2,4,6,8,10,12)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("1.Gold" = "gold2", "2.Silver" = "snow3", "3.Bronze" = "tan2"), labels = c("Gold", "Silver", "Bronze"))
